description: Two loops in same plan as blade, one of which is broken. Conical socket, deep grooves between the bevel and the socket. Base broken. Broken where blade joins the shaft. This has been mended by filling up the socket with lead and by boring holes in the socket which are filled with lead to hold the lead splint in position.
publications: Prehistoric Bronzes, 172, No catalogue,Bronzes 86. The numbers can be found in a catalogue called "Museum of Archaeology",Cambridge Antiquarian Society Catalogue, 1884.

collection: Museum of Archaeology and Ethnology, Cambridge,Foster Bequest, No. 291 (Catalogue),Prehistoric Bronzes, No. 174 (Catalogue is lost)
patina: Dark brown patches on dull metal.
description: Flat wings. A deep wide groove runs along each side of the high round socket. The outer edge of this groove is collinear with the side of the loop. The edges have a wide bevel.  In addition to the loops, there are two rivet holes.

collection: Museum of Archaeology and Ethnology, Cambridge,Foster Bequest No. 286 (Catalogue),Prehistoric Bronzes, No. 165 (Catalogue if lost),A metal label attached: A 53.
description: Flat wings and high conical socket. Edges of blade and mouth of socket chipped away. 2 rivet holes.

collection: Mason's College, Birmingham, No. 2,Given by G. H. Jack, County Surveyor for Herefordshire to E. C. Middlesex
site: England,S. Shropshire,8 miles west of Ludlow,Broardward Hall,Parish of Clungunford
description: Every vestage of the original metallic bronze has disappeared. It is simply a huge mass of (probably) carbonate of copper. The socket is still in form retains some black powder.
publications: Arch. Camb. III (4th S) 338-355, and IV 80-83 + 202-4,Evans, Anc. Br. Imps. 168, 255, 319, 320, 336, 338, 340, 397, 465,Br. Mus. Guide to Bronze Age, 1st Ed. pp. 39-85,R. L. L. Kenyon, Shrops. Anrch. Trans., IV (2nd S), 279.,Anden, Vic. Co. Hist. Shrops. I, 202.
remarks: Before being broken, the form of spear was sufficiently in evidence to justify the dotted outline.

collection: Museum, Leeds Phil. and Lit. Society.
museumCollection: Museum of Leeds Philosophical and Literary Society
description: Socket cylindrical (with slight ridge running up each side) + continued as a high, flattened midrib flat in centre and splayed or facetted at sides. Socket marked off from midrib by a hollow curved line; midrib decorated with a pattern of circles with dots in centre, lines of engraved ornament forming a triangular pattern down each side where blade joins midrib and similar pattern branching off up each side of blade, two incised bands with triangular bands encircling socket with zig-zag pattern between rivet holes across socket.

collection: Museum, Leeds Phil. and Lit. Society
museumCollection: Museum of Leeds Philosophical and Literary Society
description: Cylindrical socket contrived as a tapering midrib to the point, wings wide and thin, socket broken off below wings.
